**US Receives Over 200 New Nuclear Weapons, Largest Number Since Cold War**
The US Department of Defense received over 200 new nuclear weapons in 2023, the largest number since the Cold War, according to National Nuclear Security Administration (NNSA) Administrator Jill Hruby. She stated, 'As a result of the investments made under the administrations of Barack Obama, Donald Trump, and Joe Biden, the NNSA was able to deliver more than 200 new nuclear weapons to the Department of Defense last year. This is the largest annual delivery since the end of the Cold War,' according to the Russian TASS news agency. Hruby noted that in October 2023, the US announced a new modification to the B61 nuclear bomb, saying, 'We expect the first B61-13 unit to be produced in 2026.' The NNSA administrator added that the budget required for strategic stability programs will be around $25 billion, including $21 billion for nuclear weapons. According to Hruby, nuclear power is 'on the verge of a renaissance' amid climate change, and that 'in this case, high-enriched uranium will be used in nuclear reactors.' Hruby believes that this will pose a challenge to the current nuclear non-proliferation regime, which the US relies on. In November, Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a decree withdrawing Russia from the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty, citing the war in Ukraine and the crisis with the West. The treaty, adopted by the UN General Assembly in 1996, aims to ban all nuclear tests, but it has not been implemented due to the lack of accession by several major nuclear powers, including the US and China. In October, Russia conducted a series of missile launches to prepare its forces for a 'massive nuclear strike' in response to a similar attack.
