**US Releases Data on Its Nuclear Arsenal for the First Time in Three Years**
The United States has published recently declassified information about its nuclear arsenal to update the information last announced in October 2021. The document was published on the website of the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission and became known on July 20. According to the document, as of September 2023, the US had 3748 nuclear warheads in storage. This number is after a reduction of 88% compared to the maximum value of 31,255 at the end of the 1967 fiscal year and an additional reduction of 83% compared to the level after the fall of the Berlin Wall in late 1989. The US has dismantled 12,088 nuclear warheads from 1994 to 2023. From September 30, 2020, the US dismantled 405 nuclear warheads. Approximately 2,000 nuclear warheads are currently being removed from service and awaiting dismantling, according to the document. The US has reduced its non-strategic nuclear weapons by more than 90% since September 30, 1991. The US Nuclear Regulatory Commission notes that the nuclear stockpile includes both active and inactive warheads. Active warheads include strategic and non-strategic weapons that are maintained in a working, ready-to-use form and logistical reserves. Inactive warheads are stored on the shelf in a non-working state and their tritium balloons are removed.
