**US Publishes Declassified Information on Nuclear Weapon Stockpiles**
The United States has recently published declassified information on its nuclear weapon stockpiles. This updated information will replace the data published in October 2021. The increased transparency of nuclear weapon stockpiles is important for efforts in non-proliferation and disarmament, including obligations under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty and efforts to combat all types of nuclear weapons, including deployed, non-deployed, strategic, and non-strategic ones. As of September 2023, the US nuclear warhead stockpile consisted of 3,748 warheads. This number represents an 88% reduction compared to the maximum value (31,255) at the end of the 1967 fiscal year and an 83% decrease compared to the level (22,217) at the time of the fall of the Berlin Wall in late 1989. The US has dismantled 12,088 nuclear warheads from 1994 to 2023. From September 30, 2020, the US dismantled 405 nuclear warheads. Approximately 2,000 additional nuclear warheads have been taken out of service and are awaiting dismantling. The number of non-strategic nuclear weapons in the US has decreased by more than 90% since September 30, 1991.
